        <h3 class="jumptarget" id="about">What is the Jesuit Science Network (JSN)?</h3>

        <p>
            The Jesuit Science Network is a biographical database on Jesuit scholars in the early modern sciences,
            encompassing the period between the foundation of the Society of Jesus in 1540 and the first few decades
            after the suppression of the order in 1773. After its scheduled launch in summer/fall 2016, it will be a
            publicly available online tool that will not only allow the display of biographical data of more than 1000
            Jesuit scholars in early modern sciences, but also offer complex searches into who was doing what, when, and
            where.
        </p>

        <div class="cta">
            <div class="well text-center">
                <h4>Try out the JSN yourself</h4>
                <a href="{{ path('search') }}" class="btn btn-primary">Use advanced search</a>
                <a href="{{ path('graph') }}" class="btn btn-primary">View graphical analysis</a>
                <a href="{{ path('map') }}" class="btn btn-primary">Explore on map</a>
            </div>
            <p class="small text-center">
                <a href="{{ path('random') }}">Random database entry</a> &bull;
                <a href="{{ path('list') }}">Complete alphabetical list</a>
            </p>
        </div>

        <p>
            The origins of the JSN lie in a research project that aimed to explore how mathematical knowledge in the
            German- and French-speaking parts of Europe was put into writing and disseminated between 1650 and 1820,
            focussing on involved authors and assuming a common Jesuit root. Judged by the sheer volume of Jesuit
            writers and teachers of early modern mathematical sciences, it quickly became apparent, however, that this
            Jesuit root needed to be treated separately and by itself, eventually growing into what is now called he
            Jesuit Science Network.
        </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container container-narrow">
        <div class="col-xs-12">
        <h3 class="jumptarget" id="jesuit-science">Jesuit early modern science</h3>

        <p>
            The key interest is in Jesuits active in early modern mathematical sciences. Building on already existing
            research, the investigations for the JSN are based on Steven J. Harris' PhD thesis
            &quot;<span class="reference" data-toggle="popover" data-html="true" data-trigger="hover"
                        data-content="Harris, Steven (1988).&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Jesuit ideology &amp; Jesuit science: Scientific activity in the Society of Jesus, 1540-1773.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;PhD thesis. University of Wisconsin-Madison.">Jesuit ideology &amp; Jesuit
            science</span>&quot; from 1988.
            Harris carried out statistical surveys of Jesuit 'scientific' teaching and publishing in the early modern
            period, necessarily broadening a merely 'mathematical' focus towards one as extensive as possible in order
            to accommodate the then not yet precisely defined understanding of what nowadays would be divided into
            'mathematics' and 'natural sciences'. Harris' followup paper &quot;<span class="reference"
                                                                                     data-toggle="popover"
                                                                                     data-trigger="hover" data-html="true"
                                                                                     data-content="Harris, Steven (1997).&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Les chaires de math&eacute;matiques.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;In: Les J&eacute;suite &agrave; la Renaissance. Ed. by Luce Giard. Pairs: Presses Universitaires de France, pp. 239-261.">Les chaires de mathématiques</span>&quot;
            from 1997 offers a precise list of the topics in consideration for his own work and
            now also the JSN:
        </p>

        <dl class="dl-horizontal">
            <dt>Pure mathematics</dt>
            <dd>algebra, functions, series; analytical geometry; arithmetic; integral calculus
                and analysis; geometry; logarithms; number theory, probablitites, etc.</dd>

            <dt>Mixed mathematics</dt>
            <dd>mechanics; optics (catoptrics, dioptrics); acoustics (harmonies, theory of
                music and sound); hydraulics, civil and military architecture; mathematical geography
                (localization, cartography); scientific instruments, physics cabinet</dd>

            <dt>Astronomy</dt>
            <dd>
                calendars, almanachs, ephemerides; clocks (dials, horology); spherical astronomy; lunar and
                solar astronomy (observation and theory); comets (observation and theory); stellar astronomy (observation);
                planetary astronomy (theory)
            </dd>

            <dt>Natural philosophy</dt>
            <dd>
                commentaries of Aristotle; natural philosophy; philosophy of experience; supernatural
                and occult questions
            </dd>

            <dt>Natural history</dt>
            <dd>
                cosmography; physical, subterranean, and politcal geography; hydrography;
                meteorology (observation, instruments); zoology and botany; cabinets of curiosities, collections
            </dd>

            <dt>Medicine</dt>
            <dd>
                health and disease; anatomy, physiology, surgery; experimental medicine
            </dd>

            <dt>Agriculture and economics</dt>
            <dd>
                woods and horticulture; beekeeping; money, measure and weight
            </dd>
        </dl>
        </div>
    </div>

